# Introduction Hello World! This is my first post on this blog. I am excited to share my thoughts and ideas with you. I hope you will enjoy reading them as much as I enjoy writing them. I recently bought a Galton Board and I am fascinated by it, hence, I decided to write about it. In this post, I will discuss the device also known as Quincunx, and with it the concepts of the Binomial Distribution, Central Limit Theorem, and Pascal's Triangle. # Galton Board

(Source: [Mathworld](https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GaltonBoard.html))

The Galton Board is a device invented by Sir Francis Galton (1822â€“1911) in the late 19th century to demonstrate the Central Limit Theorem. Galton was a polymath who made significant contributions to various fields, including statistics, psychology, and biology. He further developed statistical methods of correlation and widely promted regression towards the mean. The Galton Board, also known as the Quincunx or the Bean Machine, consists of a vertical board with a number of pegs arranged in a triangular pattern. At the top of the board, there is a funnel through which balls are dropped. The balls bounce off the pegs either to the left or right with equal probability at each peg (given the symmetry of the pegs, the correct size of the balls, and the level of the board). As they fall down the board, each ball eventually comes to rest in one of the bins at the bottom. The astonishing result is that the balls always accumulate in a bell-shaped curve also known as the Gaussian or Normal Distribution. But how does this happen?
# Binomial Distribution In it's essance, the Galton Board represents a series of independent repeated trials with exactly two possible outcomes (left or right), referred to as a random Bernoulli trials [@papoulis1965random]. Each row of pegs on the Board represents a trial with the ball given a 50% chance of falling to either side. The the final position of the ball in the bins at the bottom represents the sum of $N$ such random trials. With the given number of trials $N$ and the known probability of success $p=0.5$, we can define a particular bin as the number of successes $k$ (i.e. right turns) and calculate the probability of the ball landing in that bin $P(k)$. In order to find $P(k)$, we need to calculate the number of possible ways to get $k$ successes in $N$ trials, and then multiply it by the probability $p$ of success raised to the power of $k$ and the probability of failure raised to the power of $N-k$. Mathematically, this is expressed as: $$ P(k) = \binom{N}{k} p^k (1-p)^{N-k} $$ where $$ \binom{N}{k} = \frac{N!}{k!(N-k)!} $$ ::: {#c3544cf0 .cell execution_count=1} ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: # Central Limit Theorem
